{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527313"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:30:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:30:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14203"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14203"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.51,0.01,0.23,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6889"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96058"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6889"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78790"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12734"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"},{"type":"tags","id":"12918"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29700"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96058"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is a newly graduated doctor starting her internship at a regional hospital that serves a significant Indigenous population. She has completed a standard medical curriculum but has limited experience working with Indigenous patients. The hospital is implementing a new program to improve cultural competency among its staff.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn her first day, the intern attends an orientation session about providing culturally safe care to Indigenous patients. The session emphasises the importance of understanding historical context, addressing power imbalances, and engaging in ongoing self-reflection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the approach to cultural competency being promoted by this hospital?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cultural sensitivity","Cultural awareness","Cultural blindness","Cultural safety","Cultural competence"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe approach being promoted by the hospital in this scenario is best described as \u003Cstrong\u003Ecultural safety\u003C/strong\u003E. This concept goes beyond cultural awareness, sensitivity, or competence, and emphasises the importance of addressing power imbalances, institutional discrimination, and the impact of colonization on health outcomes for Indigenous people.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECultural awareness\u003C/strong\u003E involves recognizing that cultural differences exist and can impact healthcare interactions. While this is a starting point, it does not necessarily lead to changes in behavior or practice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECultural sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E involves being respectful and considerate of cultural differences. This is an improvement over mere awareness but still falls short of the comprehensive approach described in the scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECultural competence\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the ability to interact effectively with people from different cultures. While this is important, it may still focus on learning about \u0027other\u0027 cultures without addressing systemic issues or power imbalances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECultural blindness\u003C/strong\u003E is an approach that claims not to see or recognise cultural differences. This is not appropriate in healthcare, as it can lead to ignoring important cultural factors that affect health and healthcare experiences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECultural safety, as promoted in this scenario, emphasises understanding historical context, addressing power imbalances, and engaging in ongoing self-reflection. It recognises that healthcare providers need to examine their own cultural beliefs and biases, and how these might impact their interactions with patients. Cultural safety also acknowledges the need for systemic change within healthcare institutions to better serve Indigenous patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis approach is particularly important in the context of Indigenous health, given the historical and ongoing impacts of colonization, discrimination, and systemic barriers to healthcare. By promoting cultural safety, the hospital is aiming to create an environment where Indigenous patients feel respected, empowered, and able to access culturally appropriate care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cultural safety training is essential for healthcare professionals to provide respectful and effective care to Indigenous patients.","Cultural safety goes beyond cultural awareness and sensitivity, emphasising the importance of addressing power imbalances and institutional discrimination.","Ongoing self-reflection and lifelong learning are key components of developing cultural safety in healthcare practice."],"references":["Curtis E, Jones R, Tipene-Leach D, Walker C, Loring B, Paine SJ, Reid P. Why cultural safety rather than cultural competency is required to achieve health equity: a literature review and recommended definition. International journal for equity in health. 2019 Dec;18:1-7."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78790"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14203"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78790"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T20:38:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T20:39:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6889"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96058"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description